//Merge Intervals
//Given an array of intervals where intervals[i] = [starti, endi], merge all overlapping intervals, and return an array of the non-overlapping intervals that cover all the intervals in the input.
//Example 1:
//Input: intervals = [[1,3],[2,6],[8,10],[15,18]]
//Output: [[1,6],[8,10],[15,18]]
//Explanation: Since intervals [1,3] and [2,6] overlap, merge them into [1,6].
//Example 2:
//Input: intervals = [[1,4],[4,5]]
//Output: [[1,5]]
//Explanation: Intervals [1,4] and [4,5] are considered overlapping.
//Example 3:
//Input: intervals = [[4,7],[1,4]]
//Output: [[1,7]]
//Explanation: Intervals [1,4] and [4,7] are considered overlapping.

Brute Force Approach ->

class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> merge(vector<vector<int>>& intervals) {
        int n = intervals.size();
        sort(intervals.begin(), intervals.end());
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int start = intervals[i][0];
            int end = intervals[i][1];
            if (!ans.empty() && end <= ans.back()[1])                    //Note(1)
                continue;
            for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                if (intervals[j][0] <= end) {
                    end = max(end, intervals[j][1]);
                } else {
                    break;
                }
            }
            ans.push_back({start, end});
        }
        return ans;
    }
};


Time Complexity ->
O(n²)
Reason:
For each interval i, we may scan all subsequent intervals using the inner loop.
Space Complexity ->
O(n)
Reason:
In the worst case, no intervals overlap, so all n intervals are stored in the answer vector.

Optimal Approach ->

class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> merge(vector<vector<int>>& intervals) {
        sort(intervals.begin(), intervals.end());
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        for (auto &interval : intervals) {
            if (ans.empty() || ans.back()[1] < interval[0]) {        // Note(2)
                ans.push_back(interval);
            } else {
                ans.back()[1] = max(ans.back()[1], interval[1]);
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};


Time Complexity ->
O(n log n)
Reason:
Sorting takes O(n log n).
After sorting, each interval is visited exactly once in a single traversal O(n).
Therefore:
O(n log n) + O(n)
= O(n log n)
Space Complexity ->
O(n)
Reason:
In the worst case, no intervals overlap, so every interval is stored in the answer vector.
Hence the answer vector can contain n intervals.

Corner Cases

1. Single Interval
[[1,5]]
Output:
[[1,5]]

2. Fully Overlapping
[[1,10],[2,3],[4,5]]
Output:
[[1,10]]

3. Touching Intervals
[[1,4],[4,5]]
Output:
[[1,5]]
Because:
4 <= 4
is considered overlapping.

4. Unsorted Input
[[4,7],[1,4]]
After sorting:
[[1,4],[4,7]]
Merged:
[[1,7]]



